thread.title: Sarajevo To Dubrovnik
thread.title_full: Sarajevo To Dubrovnik - FlyerTalk Forums

posts.author: DanielW
posts.text:
For only €64 a night including breakfast, I couldn't resist spending my only night in Sarajevo at such an historic hotel. After storing my bag at the hotel reception, I headed out for a walk through the city.
Some of the buildings still had damage from the war over 20 years ago.
The stylized snowflake logo of the 1984 Winter Olympics on the pavement.
Men playing chess in Trg oslobođenja (Liberation Square), that is dedicated to Alija Izetbegović . Izetbegović became the first President of the newly-independent Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina in 1992.
Outside Gradska tržnica (City market).
And some tasty and interesting local food for sale inside.
Vječna vatra , a memorial to the victims of the Second World War in Sarajevo. The city was occupied for four years during the war by by Nazi Germany and the fascist Independent State of Croatia.
Outside the Sarajevo National Theatre for the meet up point for the Sarajevo walking tour .

posts.title: Patio Doors & Vinyl Windows In Oshkosh And Stevens Point Come In Varied Range Of Features & Styles
posts.text:
Among the various types of doors available in the market, patio doors are mostly preferred as they offer both aesthetic appeal and functionality. Moreover, now days the patio doors are not just limited to traditional swinging doors as they are now available in varied designs and styles that can match all types of home. 
Patio doors are usually ideal for back doors and are often preferred over other types of doors since they tend to be energy efficient and offer enhanced security and protection and usually come with a standard lock. 
For all those who are planning to invest in patio doors in Appleton and Eau Claire can go through the below mentioned tips: 
Styles : Patio doors are available in various styles such as sliding patio doors, folding patio doors and swinging patio doors. Depending on the décor of the home, budget and requirement; one can choose the patio door accordingly. However, it is important to note that swinging patio doors require more room to open and are ideal for rooms that are spacious. Rooms with limited space can opt for sliding or folding patio doors as they tend to take less space. Patio doors and vinyl windows in Oshkosh and Stevens Point are available in various styles and designs to match the décor of the home 
Materials : Even though the patio doors are available in varied designs but when it comes to construction; they are available in certain limited materials such as vinyl, fiberglass, steel, aluminum, wood and clad-wood. Those who want to opt for patio doors that offer a feel and look of genuine wood but require less maintenance can go for fiberglass patio doors. Moreover, the doors made from fiberglass have the ability to withstand any type of weather and temperature. On the other hand, those who want to opt for patio doors that can resist corrosion and cost-effective compared to wood can choose aluminum doors. 
Energy Efficiency : As glass forms the most important part of the patio doors; one should select the right type of glass that offers maximum benefits and efficiency. One should choose patio doors that are made from glasses that help to lower energy bills all year and prevents ultra violet rays from entering. For those who are looking forward to get maximum privacy and added style, then decorative tempered glass perhaps is the best option available. 
Durability: Another important thing that one should look for when choosing a patio door is whether it is durable and can be maintained easily. 
Customized options: It is important to note that all homes are different and thus the standard size patio doors don’t always fit every home appropriately. This is why some manufacturers have come with customized patio door options that can suit the size and requirement of almost all homes. 
Thus, it can be said patio doors are preferred by most homeowners because of their flexibility, look and functionality.

thread.section_title: Trip Reports - FlyerTalk Forums
thread.title: Sarajevo To Dubrovnik
thread.title_full: Sarajevo To Dubrovnik - FlyerTalk Forums

posts.author: DanielW
posts.text:
Our guide for the day, Neno, who had lived as a child in Sarajevo during the siege of the city during the Bosnian War. With the communist era apartment blocks being easy targets for Serbian snipers, his family had to live in the building basement.
He gave us a brief history of Sarajevo, and how it was founded by the Ottomans in the 1450's. Due to taxes imposed by the Ottomans on other religions, many local Christians converted to Islam at this time. Neno said he himself is agnostic and although his mother is nominally muslim, she has only been to a mosque twice in her life.
Back at Liberation Square, with Cathedral Church of the Nativity of the Theotokos in the background.
Outside our next stop, Sarajevo Synagogue . Designed by Karel Pařík and built in 1902 in the Moorish Revival which was a popular choice for synagogues in the Ottoman empire. Following the expulsion of Jews from Spain in the 15th century, and the invitation from the Ottoman Empire to resettle their population, Sephardic Jews migrated to Sarajevo . The majority of the Jewish community in Sarajevo were sadly killed however in the Holocaust during the Nazi Occupation in World War 2.
We then headed east along the Miljacka river.
Latin Bridge over the Miljacka . The northern side of the bridge is the site of the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria by Gavrilo Princip in 1914, which eventually helped precipitate the start of World War I.

thread.section_title: Trip Reports - FlyerTalk Forums
thread.title: Sarajevo To Dubrovnik
thread.title_full: Sarajevo To Dubrovnik - FlyerTalk Forums

posts.author: DanielW
posts.text:
Neno gave us a 10 minute break and suggested morning tea at a bakery over the road, where I bought a Zeljanica pastry.
Emperor's Mosque , originally built in the mid-fifteenth century but soon damaged and totally destroyed, and then rebuilt in 1565.
The brewery and headquarters of Sarajevska pivara , founded in 1864. Neno said that the brewery was situated over a spring, and hence helped to continue beer production during the siege of Sarajevo .
Looking over to Vijećnica , or Sarajevo City Hall, on the northern side of the Miljacka . In August 25th, 1992, Serbian shelling during the Siege of Sarajevo set fire to over 2 million books at the City Hall. After years of restoration, the building was finally reopened in 2014.
We then continued on to Baščaršija , Sarajevo's old bazaar.
Hundreds of pigeons in Baščaršija square. In the background is the Sebilj , a pseudo-Ottoman-style wooden fountain.
Built in 1462, Baščaršija is the historical and cultural center of the city.

thread.section_title: Trip Reports - FlyerTalk Forums
thread.title: Sarajevo To Dubrovnik
thread.title_full: Sarajevo To Dubrovnik - FlyerTalk Forums

posts.author: DanielW
posts.text:
Enjoy Sarajevo .
Gazi Husrev-beg Mosque situated inside Baščaršija , where people were performing the midday Zuhr prayer.
And at the Sarajevo Caravanserai where we ended our walking tour. The Caravanserai had been converted into a space for artists. I thanked Neno for the very interesting tour and introduction to Sarajevo.
For lunch I headed to a restaurant in Baščaršija and had some Ćevapi . Made from grilled meat, onion and flatbread, it is a national dish in Bosnia and Herzegovina and Serbia.
Walking past Katedrala Srca Isusova as I headed west back along Ferhadija Street.
And back at the Hotel Holiday, ready to check-in.
After being bought by an Austrian businessman in 2003 for a reported $23 million, it lost its famous Holiday Inn branding in 2011 and subsequently fell into bankruptcy in 2015 .
It was purchased by a Bosnian businessman Rasim Bajrović in 2016, who returned to its '80s roots.
My room for my one night, complete with classic 1980s décor. It was like stepping back in time, with the navy blue carpet, mahogany furnishings and bright yellow retro bathroom ceramics. Quite a delight!

An interesting display outside the ruined building of the Historical Museum of Bosnia and Herzegovina.
A yellow Tatra K2 tram from the Czech Republic, dating from the 1970's.
And back at the Hotel Holiday. I was really loving the retro 80's interior!
In the evening I headed out for a walk through the city again.
Damage to a building left over from the war.
Blue skies finally appearing after the overcast day.
I wasn't too hungry after the late lunch so enjoyed a hot chocolate and some Tufahije (a Bosnian dessert consisting of a walnut-stuffed apple stewed in water and sugar) for a very sweet dinner.
I then walked along Maršala Tita back to the hotel after a great first day in the Balkans.

posts.text:
After resting up at the hotel for a bit, I headed for a walk up the hill to Vraca Memorial Park where there was a derelict memorial to comrade Tito , the first and only President of Yugoslavia.
From the hill there was good views of Sarajevo below.
Looking down on some of the houses and roads on the south side of the Miljacka .
The centre of town with the National Museum of Bosnia and Herzegovina at bottom left, the bright yellow Hotel Holiday at centre and the Parliament of Bosnia and Herzegovina on the bottom right.
A closer view from above of the Hotel Holiday.
Sarajevo Central Railway Station.

posts.author: DanielW
posts.text:
Day 2.
Breakfast in the hotel at the start of day 2.
During the siege of Sarajevo , the hotel staff, some dodging snipers' bullets on the way to work, managed to master the art of hostelry in wartime . Food for the guests was often cooked on an open fire in the kitchen, and oil for the hotel's electricity generator was bought on the black market with the foreign currency brought in by the foreign journalists.
A wartime photo of the hotel staff keeping up appearances for the New Year's Eve buffet in 1993, despite the numerous challenges of operating a hotel in a city under siege.
Quite a decent breakfast from the buffet.
And I couldn't resist having some of the baklava too.
After checking out of the hotel, I headed out to the bus station to begin my journey south.
The plan for the next few days was to first head to Mostar for a night and then head over the border to Kotor in Montenegro. I would then head to Dubrovnik in Croatia for two nights.
At Autobuska Stanica Sarajevo, where I joined the queue to pay the €1 bus station fee. I had booked and paid all my bus station tickets for the trip online, but had to pay for bus station and luggage fees on the day.

There was a post in 2011 about the importance of eyebrow maintenance.
